Count modeling tutorial, anterior mouse brain

Objective

The purpose of this analysis and function is to determine what Canonical components are associated to which genes in the anterior mouse brain.

dt = readRDS('C:\\Users\\Juan\\Desktop\\Nancy modeling CC\\Brain.rds')

coordintes = read_csv('C:\\Users\\Juan\\Desktop\\Nancy modeling CC\\spatial_coordinates.csv')
New names:Rows: 2696 Columns: 3-- Column specification ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Delimiter: ","
chr (1): ...1
dbl (2): imagerow, imagecol
i Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
i Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
count_mat = dt@assays$Spatial@counts %>% as.matrix() %>% t() %>% as.data.frame()


spatial_cc = readRDS('C:\\Users\\Juan\\Desktop\\Nancy modeling CC\\CC_spatial_driven.rds')
genes_interest = readRDS('C:\\Users\\Juan\\Desktop\\Nancy modeling CC\\Filtered_gene.rds')

nUMI = dt@meta.data$nCount_SCT


###
#   Quick way to determine the top variables genes
#

variances <- apply(count_mat, 2, var)
variances <- variances[!grepl("-", names(variances))]
#variances <- variances[!grepl("^\\d", names(variances))]


sorted_genes <- sort(variances, decreasing = T)
X <- 500  # change this to your desired value

# Get the names of the top X variable genes
top_X_variable_genes <- names(sorted_genes[1:X])
dt = count_mat[,top_X_variable_genes] # Overwriting the original, for RAM purposes

## Adding the nUMI 

dt$nUMI = nUMI
dt$cell = rownames(dt)

spatial_cc$cell = rownames(spatial_cc)


genes_interest = c(top_X_variable_genes)
dt$nUMI = nUMI
dt$cell = rownames(dt)

Overview of data

This is what data should be inputted. It contains metadata and count data together.

###
#   Merging the the CCs on the expression so it can be easily modeled 

dt =
  dt %>% 
    left_join(spatial_cc)
Joining with `by = join_by(cell)`
head(dt) # this also contains the metadata combined in order for the function to work

Plotted picture of the data of the anterior mouse brain

First lets run all the outcome variables (genes) to see which genes are associated with the Canonical components. We run the multimodel_count_regression function with estimate = TRUE.

Association of genes with CCs

Average count effect

To visually determine where the outcome variables of interest are associated with the CCs. We plot the mean and variance of all gene expression

results = multimodel_count_regression(outcomes_interest= genes_interest,  # a vector of genes of interest
                                  models=   c("GLM", "ZeroInflated", "ZeroInflNegBinomial", "NegativeBinomial", "Hurdle")
,          # a vector of models to use (e.g., "GLM", "ZeroInflated", etc.)
                                  plot_density= F,    # a logical value, if TRUE, plots density
                                  plot_qq= F,         # a logical value, if TRUE, plots Q-Q plot
                                  estimate = F,        # a logical value, if TRUE, calculates estimates
                                  avg_effect  = T,        # a logical value, if TRUE, log-transforms the plots
                                  rootogram = F,       # a logical value, if TRUE, creates rootogram
                                  full_model = '~ CC1 + log(nUMI)' ,      # a formula describing the full model to be tested
                                  null_model = '~ log(nUMI)',      # a formula describing the null model to be compared with the full model
                                  data  = dt,      #  data set to use for the analysis, MUST BE COUNT DATA NOT LOG NORMALIZED
                                  workers = 4,
                                  path = 'C:\\Users\\Juan\\Desktop\\Nancy modeling CC\\temp_results') # path to save

Volcano plot

To visually determine the genes that are associated with the CCs, we are only going to grab those that are of in range (inf,-0.1) , (0.1, inf).



threshold_pval <- -log(0.05/5000)
threshold_est = 10
  
estimates %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = Estimate, y = -log(lrt_pval), color = ifelse((-log(lrt_pval) > threshold_pval) & (abs(Estimate) > threshold_est), "above", "below"))) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("above" = "red", "below" = "black")) +
  theme_classic() +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = -10), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 10), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_hline(aes(yintercept = threshold), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  facet_wrap(~model)+
  theme(legend.position = "none")
